      "title": "Behind the curtain",
      "description": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Behind the curtain"
                }
              ],
              "isBold": true
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "New Kendall"
                }
              ],
              "isBold": true
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "January 18, 2099"
                }
              ],
              "isBold": true
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "<$Scr_Ps::0>"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Mik!”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "It was Junior on his Voice."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“What the fuck, Junior. It’s like 6 AM.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I know you ain’t slept. Meet me up by the old water tower. Half hour. We need to talk.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Yeah, OK, see you.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Junior was right. Laying awake all night, replaying the whole thing, every time he closed his eyes he heard shots. Which was weird, because in the storm he hadn"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’t heard a thing. Just the awkward motions of people dropping, then realizing they had been shot. And killed? He was sure of it."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "He walked away from Mass Ave toward the old stone tower that had been at the top of Park Street for centuries. It was falling down now, but all the kids knew how to get inside, where there was still a room that no one could see or hear from the outside. Junior was already there."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“What are we going to do?” Junior asked, nervous and pacing."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Do? Why do we have to do something?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Because we saw it all. You think they’re going to let us just walk around and tell everyone?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“They shot some fugees. What’s new? I mean, it was horrible, but not the first time.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Yeah, and do you know anyone else who saw the other times?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Junior was crazing him now. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“You think we’re in danger?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I’m just saying, we need to think very carefully about our next moves.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Next moves? This isn’t a vid, Junior. Our next move is to go to school tomorrow, like we would do anyway.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Yeah, OK, maybe that’s a good start.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“It won’t be enough,” a girl’s voice said from the dark side of the room. Nila stepped into the light filtering in through a hole in the wall."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“What the fuck, Nila,” Mik said. “What are you, a spy for the Secs? You following us?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“No, idiot,” she said. “I’m trying to help you. Yeah, my mom is a Sec, I know. You think the Secs want any part of me?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "They both laughed. If Nila wasn"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’t so wicked smart, New Kendall would have marched her across the Broadway bridge years ago."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I heard my mom talking to work,” she said. “At least four people died out there where you were. The fugees are all up about it, they want blood. You better hope the honchos don’t decide you’ll do for a token peace offering.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Would they do that?” Mik asked."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Nila shrugged. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Do you want me to find out?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“We’re so fucked,” Junior said. “What are we going to do?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Mik thought about it. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Nothing. We keep our mouths shut. If anyone asks us what happened during the storm, we couldn’t see anything in the driving rain.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“And what about that tool, Wong?” Junior asked. “He knows we did see it.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Exactly why he’s going to be happy we’re keeping quiet,” Mik said. “They’re just going to blame him, he doesn’t need any witnesses saying they weren’t armed, or that it was very unlikely they would have made it across the drowned bridge. I mean, it sounds ridiculous they even tried.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Yeah, that could work,” Nila said. “Let’s hope.”<!$Scr_Ps::0>"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "*****"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "<$Scr_Ps::0>Twenty-four hours later, Mik was still walking around free. No one had put a black bag over his head and taken him to be interrogated, or whatever it was that the Secs did when you were on their shitlist. Here he was, walking around school at 10 in the morning like nothing happened. In a way, he was disappointed, a bit outraged even, that nobody was talking about any of it. Maybe they didn"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’t know about the shootings, but everyone knew the storm had been big. And most of them had heard that the waters would not be receding now that another glacier had taken a dive. He saw Nila at the other end of the hall making furtive eyeball gestures at him of the “come here” variety, but he wanted to ignore her. Instead, she trotted over to him."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“He’s here!” she said, forcing the words out between clenched teeth so that no one could hear her."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“What?” he said. “Who’s here?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“The man,” she said. “REM.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“What? No "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " you mean?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Yes, Raefe,” she said. “Downstairs, in the Corp. office.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“You saw him?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Not exactly, but I know he’s here. I think they’re talking about…what we talked about yesterday.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“No shit!” he said. “Oh man, this is not going to be good.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Why do you say that?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I mean, I know he’s super cool and all that, but this has to be trouble. I don’t need trouble.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "She laughed. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Don’t believe everything you hear. He is cool, for sure.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Man, I wonder what’s going on down there.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“If we can get close, I think I can figure it out,” she said."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“What, you think we can listen at the door? Oh, wait, you can’t…”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Yeah, some. Keep it to yourself, though.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Completely, he thought. Now it all made sense, Nila"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’s attitude. She was an empath. The Corp. kept them out of the town "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " they needed them for certain activities (not that he knew what), but they were frowned on here in New Kendall."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“My lips are sealed. How close do you have to get?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I don’t know. I’ve never been around someone like him. He can tangle with the whole world.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Why don’t you try here?” Mik asked. “There’s no class in that room for the next hour. I’m supposed to be doing independent study, so no one will miss me. You?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Yeah, the same. So that works.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "No one was around. They ducked in the room and took their puters out so it would like they were working. Nila sat still, her expression distant for a second, then she nodded."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Man, I can feel his mind so clearly.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“You can just read his thoughts?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“No, silly. He has to let me. I let him know I was here and I wanted to listen in. He can feel I’m not trying to harm him. He wants kids in New Kendall to understand what’s going on. To understand what Everywhere is really about.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "All his friends talked about this a lot. New Kendall, their parents, no one wanted to talk about Everywhere. And Raefe Epstein Miller, he was maybe like their least favorite person in the world. What was he up to? The net was full of stuff, some of it fantastic, some of it horrifying, most of it hard to know if it was true or even real. But here he was, his friend tangled up with the most famous empath in the world."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "He started to ask Nila what was going on, but she waved him silent, saying just, "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Not now.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "They sat there for about a half hour. He watched a drama unfold on her face as she followed the action. Her expression got more serious, than angry, then determined. Finally, she looked up."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“After school. The tower. Bring Junior. Tell no one.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "And then she ran out, leaving him alone and confused. He still had time before his next class. He heard a commotion outside the building. He looked out the window. Half a dozen Secs were escorting an old man, two younger women and a middle-aged man down the street. Their attention was definitely on the old guy. He was thin, with tight gray curls. He was wearing old clothes. Mik realized with a start that it was REM. He had never seen a picture of him, but he hardly looked like the threat to civilization that his parents made him out to be."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "He went through the rest of the day on autopilot, his head still spinning from the last few days. He hadn"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’t had much of a sixteenth birthday, but it was starting to feel like some kind of vid game where had just passed through a new level and now had possession of new magical knowledge. Only he didn’t know what it was or what he was supposed to do with it. He sent Junior a message about meeting up, making it clear not to bring anyone else."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "It was windy and cloudy by the time he got to the tower, barely visible in the nearly moonless winter dusk. The temperature had dropped to 40, everything was still damp from the storm. Junior and Nila were already there."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Good,” Nila said. “You’re here. I told Junior the basics.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“So what happened?” Mik asked. Nila could be dramatic sometimes, and he wasn’t in the mood."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“It was amazing!” she said. “He knew I was there. He wanted me "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " us "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " to know. He thinks New Kendall lies to us and if we knew what was going on, we would want to change it.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“What’s he like?” Junior asked. “I mean, you hear all these things…”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“He’s…kind,” she said. “I don’t really know. I’m new to this whole mind meld thing. I mean, I’ve never actually had a conversation with anyone this way. I feel stuff coming off people, but I’ve never done this.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“So you tangled?” Junior asked."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Yeah, now that you say it, I guess that’s what we did,” she said."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“So what happened?” Mik asked. “Who was there, what did they talk about?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Raefe was there with two people from Everywhere "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " Tosh and Sura "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " and a fugee named Ines. And from our side, it was the head of Sec, Major Sindh, and some tool named Bartlow, no idea what he does besides listen to himself talk. Raefe said that Everywhere was there to represent the people on the other side of the river, and that they were all upset about Saturday night. Four fugees died, and two more are in tough shape. He wanted to know why the Secs fired on the fugees.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“So what did Sindh say?” Mik asked."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“He started to talk and Bartlow jumped in. He was all ‘in the opinion of the corporation, nyak, nyak, illegal actions, threatening our personnel, nyak, nyak, we regret,’ and all that bullshit. But Everywhere weren’t impressed. Ines was ‘so you were concerned that a dozen unarmed, half drowned homeless people in a dead truck were going to overwhelm a company of armed soldiers behind a fortified checkpoint? And that’s why you killed them?’ And Sindh was like ‘We gave them fair warning. We had no choice when they took aggressive actions.’”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Fair warning! That’s a lie!” Junior said. “He told them to stand down. They never said stop or we’ll shoot. Or fired warning shots. It was ‘Hold up!’ and then bam, bam, bam.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“And they weren’t being aggressive,” Mik added. “A woman threw a line across and clipped on to it. She was going to zip out of the river. The water was fast and rising. Sons of bitches! So what did Everywhere do?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“So Tosh was trying to keep Ines from jumping across the table. That was her, I suspect, on the zip line. Raefe was calm, but inside, fierce. He told them they wanted guarantees that this would never happen again. He said New Kendall has to discipline the officers in charge. And make reparations to the fugees. Something about rebuilding the bus yard.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“So throw Sindh under the bus and pay off the fugees,” Mik said, slightly disappointed. “I guess that’s all they could expect, anyway.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“No, it wasn’t just that,” Ines said. “Because then he told them New Kendall is now almost completely surrounded by water and it won’t recede because of the latest big ice that fell in. And that New Kendall can’t survive on its own any more than Everywhere. He wants New Kendall "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " not the whole corp, just the town "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " to agree that we and Everywhere will always help each other when life is at stake. They don’t want anymore people to die like that.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Well, that’s interesting,” Junior said. “New Kendall likes to say Everywhere can only get in one way, but now they flipped it.  Hah! You can only get out one way. Sindh couldn’t have liked that. What did he say?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Barlow cut him off again,” Nila said. “’Must consult with, we appreciate your coming here,’ nyak, nyak. And then, this was so cool, Raefe let me know that he could sense that it was all bullshit. I mean, anyone could. But the cool thing was that he knew that Barlow was thinking about how to spin this to the top brass, and was wondering if they should throw Sindh under the bus. And Sindh was thinking maybe he should throw Wong under the bus!”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Yeah, that sounds like the New Kendall we all know and love,” Mik said. “Not too sentimental. Dry land, dry eyes. Junior, I think we’re cool. They’re going to be worrying about bigger stuff.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“You bet,” Nila said. “Because right after Barlow tried to shut them up with all that ‘must consult’ stuff, Ines cut in. I don’t think she’s really with Everywhere. She’s like some fugee rogue. She told Barlow that the Norcamb fugees wanted blood, but they had agreed to let Raefe do his thing, and now she was wondering if that wasn’t a mistake. She gave him 24 hours to come up with a reply that wouldn’t send them over the edge. Raefe didn’t say anything. I think he wanted Barlow to understand shit is getting real.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Man, shit is getting fucked up,” Junior said."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“So you can tangle now with this Raefe guy?” Mik asked. “Anytime, anywhere?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Maybe,” Nila said. “Why? You want to send him a message?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Maybe someday,” Mik agreed. “Just good to know that you can talk. So what are we going to do now?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "In the end, they agreed, nothing. This was too big for the three of them, and they had no idea what to do. Nila said she would write down a transcript of what she had heard through Raefe"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’s mind and put it somewhere safe, so they had proof if they ever needed it. They went their separate ways, glad for the dark to give them cover."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Later, Mik sat listlessly eating dinner while his parents chattered about their usual meaningless stuff. He stared out the dining room window, the well-lit streets of New Kendall fanned out down the hill. And then, darkness surrounding their self-made island in all directions, just as Raefe had described. He thought of Nila and Raefe tangled up and was surprised to find he was deeply jealous.<!$Scr_Ps::0>"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Raefe negotiates with NK, prevents a war. Mik learns Nila can entangle and she tells him and Jr what happened."
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        }
      ],
