      "id": 9,
      "lineId": 1,
      "beatId": 1,
      "bookId": 1,
      "positionWithinLine": 8,
      "positionInBeat": 0,
      "title": "Nila and Mik get closer",
      "description": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "<$Scr_Ps::0>Nila seemed to have quite a supply of meeting places that she thought were safe from prying eyes. Between classes she had told Mik to meet her this evening in an abandoned building near the Alewife. You had to walk past the building, turn down an alley that was nearly hidden by a big tree and then enter a rusted old door near the back. He had brought a flashlight like she said, finding his way down some sketchy stairs to a basement."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I’m over here,” she said from a dark corner. She had a small battery-powered light she turned on. She must come here often, he thought. There was an old sofa on a rug in the corner. “The stairs in the main entrance are collapsed, so Sec didn’t think anyone could come down here. They don’t have any surveillance below the first floor.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "She hugged him a little tighter than usual."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“You okay?” he asked."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Yeah, yeah. But there’s a lot to tell you.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "She told him about her trip to Chiang Mei."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Did you see any elephants?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Just a shrine to them. They’re gone now, extinct.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“No!” he protested. “Mr. Alvarez said New K had revived them.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“He lied.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Sons of bitches. I always wanted to see one, in person.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Well, I did, but it was a dead one. They must have been magnificent. Huge. Enormous feet. And of course, that funny trunk. But I found out some bad shit.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Worse than no more elephants?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Okay, maybe not. But it turns out my mom is not just some Sec grunt. Robertson was there, and he knew her by name, like they were old friends. She introduced me to him And she gave some kind of talk to all the New K honchos.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“No shit! About what?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Uh, it’s hard to explain. I couldn’t really hear all of it. Seems like they’re stepping up their snooping on tanglers.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Huh. I guess I’m not surprised. Why do you think they’re doing that now? We’ve been at odds with Everywhere for decades. And what was Robertson like?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Creepy. And I don’t know why now. I could guess. But I was scared, Mik. What if they find out about me?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Yeah, I hear you. Won’t your mom protect you?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I don’t know. And if she did, I’m afraid it would have a price. Like becoming a New K tool. I feel trapped.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "He could feel her fear, her need for reassurance. Without thinking, he put his arms around her, drawing her to his chest. She folded herself into him. He could feel her warmth, feel her relax just a bit as he cradled the back of her head with his hand. They stood there for a second, still, just feeling each other"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’s breathing. She looked up at him, her expression hard to read. He felt a rush of feelings."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "He touched his lips with his index finger. She nodded and did the same. He pulled her head gently toward him and kissed her. It became a long kiss, passed back and forth, a wordless, rising conversation. A minute ago, she had seemed a mass of neediness. Now her needs seemed more focused."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "She took his hand and led him to the couch. He realized that he had been anxious about just such a moment. She was older, probably had been with more people than he had, was more skilled. As exciting as that was, it was also a bit scary. But they undressed each other with about the same mix of fumbling and calm and he felt more able to forget his fears and focus on her now. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "She wrapped them both in the blanket that had been covering the back of the couch. She seemed to sense his anxieties and climbed on top of him. She was light and strong and felt entirely alive to his touch. He closed his eyes and let his hands explore her, finding the places that pleased her. She leaned forward, kissing him, letting her breasts graze his chest. After a bit, she reached down between her legs and took him inside her, her heat and wetness grasping him, pulling him in. A little voice in his head worried that she could read his thoughts. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "A somewhat louder voice suggested good, since she could "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "feel"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " his thoughts, for chrissakes, inside her, so stop worrying. And then he felt her fingers digging into his shoulder slightly, as if to say, hey, I"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’m here, and he realized that voice had been her, inside his head. He looked up, opening his eyes. In the half-dark, her eyes were closed, but there was a wild smile on her face and a feeling of joy washed him over him. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "And then her hips seemed to be telling him something. He found her rhythm and soon all he could think of was their motion. And then he couldn"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’t think at all, as they spiraled inwards together to climax."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "She rolled off him, squeezing  him toward the back of the couch. He lay on his side to accommodate her. She played with his hair a bit and then popped up and started getting dressed. So he did, too. Finally, she broke the silence."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“That was nice. I was wondering if we’d ever get to that.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "He wondered if she had asked him to this place just to "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“get to that.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "She smiled. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“No silly, I didn’t ask you here just to fuck you. Don’t underestimate yourself "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " you are really a very reassuring and compassionate person. A half hour ago I was a quivering wreck. Now I’m just quivering, thanks to you.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Happy to help,” he said, not knowing how to respond. He had no idea that he could be reassuring to anyone."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Don’t worry,” she said, “I won’t hold you to it, if that’s what’s bothering you.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“No, I wasn’t worried. Or bothered, I don’t think. I like you, you must know that. And I’d be lying if I didn’t admit that I, too, had been wondering if we were ever going to take the next step.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Easy, boy. One day at a time.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "He blushed. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I didn’t mean it that way. Don’t worry, I’m not going to ask you to marry me.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "She laughed. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Good, because right now I’m not looking to say ‘no’ to you. Let’s leave it at ‘yes, that was fun and nice and we found something together.’ Because I don’t know what tomorrow will bring and neither do you,”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "And that was the problem, he realized. He hated not knowing what tomorrow would bring. It usually brought shit "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " more crap at school and home, more floods, more worries about what job he"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’d be stuck with. But he needed to know."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“When we were…were you inside my head?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Was I?” she asked. “I’m sorry, I guess I got carried away, you know…I shouldn’t have done that.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“No, it was OK. Sex is weird sometimes "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " you feel these overwhelming things but you have no idea if the other person is feeling the same thing. And there you were. It was…reassuring, I guess.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Happy to help,” she said. “I guess that’s as much reassurance as I can give right now. I can’t see the future anymore than you. And yeah, it bothers me, too. Maybe I’ve learned to live with that more than you.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Ah, he realized. All that enactor stuff, her rebel image, that was her learning to live with uncertainty. Something to be said for that."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I think I hear your thoughts a bit now,” he said. “I seem to sense things about you. I don’t think it’s because I’m a good listener or because you’re telling me them.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Cool,” she said. “I think it’s because I trust you. I let you sense them without realizing it.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Maybe you should be careful,” he said. “Given the new circumstances.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Oh, don’t worry, I don’t trust that many people,” she said.<!$Scr_Ps::0>"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "<$Scr_Ps::1>*****<!$Scr_Ps::1>"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "<$Scr_Ps::0>Shit, what have I done, she thought, walking back from her little hidey hole. He"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’s a good kid, I like him, and it was a fun, sweet romp. A bit more actually "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " they had connected there for a while. But shit is already too complicated. Is he going to want to come with me when I go? Do I want him to?"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Her mind buzzed: And what if he doesn"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’t, and my feelings for him get more intense? I’ll hate him for making me stay. I have to avoid these moments of opening myself up, she thought, it will only put me in danger. No, that’s not right, either, she argued with herself. What’s the point of having empathic skills if I can’t be an empath, either to myself or him? "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Maybe she"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’d try to find REM and ask him how he dealt with these moments. Or would he just think she’s a silly teenage girl? He’s old enough to be my grandfather, for fuck’s sake, she thought."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Her face was still flushed from sex, and the night air felt cool against it. It was too much to figure out now and she just let the heat and the coolness mix, feeling like somehow it was a metaphor for something. The answer would come, in time.<!$Scr_Ps::0>"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Nila is very excited about meeting Raefe. She tells Mik about it. He feels her mind more than usual. He wonders if he is becoming an empath."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "She feels him feeling her and things start to get physical. They get swept up in it and wind up having sex. She is nonchalant about that, he is not. The experience was far more intimate and consuming than his prior ones. He feels closer to her but resisting the notion of love. Not sure why."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "She senses this, but doesn"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’t say anything. She too is ambivalent, since she knows he may not come with her and is not sure she wants to get more involved."
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        }
