    {
      "id": 13,
      "lineId": 1,
      "beatId": 1,
      "bookId": 1,
      "positionWithinLine": 12,
      "positionInBeat": 0,
      "title": "Mik talks to his dad",
      "description": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "<$Scr_Ps::0>Mik had told his parents the news and they had taken it well enough. But he knew they weren"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’t finished with him. He had been dreading another Talk About His Future, and making himself appropriately scarce. But they knew he would have to make his final decision this week, and he knew they would find a way to lobby him for their plan for his life. And now that moment had come."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Under the guise of shopping for a suit to wear to graduation, Larry had maneuvered him into a trip to New Kendall"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’s one mall. Or “nice for the men in the family to have a day out,” as Larry put it. Nice for whom, Mik wondered. He doubted his dad really enjoyed this, either."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "But here they were, taking the 20 minute walk to the store. Larry burbled on about his fantasy football team leading the league in goals, how clothing sales were up in so many parts of the world, things were getting better, the new century was going to be exciting, and then he just seemed to run out of inane things to say and they walked quietly."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“So, listen, before we get to the store, I just wanted to make sure you’re set with your choice this week. I know it can be hard to sort it out. If you want to brainstorm, happy to do that.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Thanks, dad. I think I’m pretty set on AI interfacer. Like I told you before, it’s something that interests me and I think I could be good at it.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I’d like to think my son could be good at almost anything,” Larry said. “And that if the corporation also thinks you’d be good at marketing or logistics, that it’s worth considering why.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“They don’t tell you that,” Mik said. “It might have nothing to do with me. Maybe they just need more of those people. They didn’t even give Junior a choice. They’re sending him to learn some Indonesian language just because he looks vaguely like people over there and they’re desperate to crack that part of the world.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I think you’re being a bit cynical there,” Larry said. “I’m sure there’s more to it than that.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Mik let it sit. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Anyway, I did think about marketing and logistics. The truth is, I don’t care at all about stuff like marketing. What does it matter who buys what from whom? Really? It’s not like anybody cares if everyone actually has food and clothing "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " they just want to make sure the people who buy it buy it from New Kendall.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Guilty as charged,” Larry said. “And why not? If they buy it from us, we know it’s well made, it won’t kill you, and the money won’t go to some warlord somewhere who will use it to buy guns and cause more trouble.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Ah, the "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“we’re the good guys” speech, Mik thought."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I get that there are bad people in the world, dad. I’m not four years old. But are we always the good guys?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“We’re not perfect, Mik. I know you have your criticisms and that’s normal. How will things change if you don’t get involved?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I wish I believed that things would change if people listened to us kids. But I can’t find any examples. We’re the ones who change. We get on the treadmill and the corporation tells us when to run and how fast.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Whoa, son. Who have you been talking to?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“No one, dad. And everyone. Lots of people think that.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Not in my experience. But if you feel that way, how is being an AI interfacer any different? I just worry that you are backing yourself into a dead end because you’ve somehow formed a very negative opinion of things around here. And you’ll just get more frustrated when it turns out to be a dead end. Whereas, if you got involved with more dynamic areas like marketing, you’d get a chance to experience what New Kendall is all about. Be part of something bigger.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Mik weighed his words. One part of him wanted to tell him about the night on the bridge. Another part knew that could spiral out of control and go places he didn"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’t want to know about, much less go to."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Aren’t we all part of something bigger anyway? Isn’t everyone just trying to learn how to live in this messed up world that constantly surprises us with unexpected storms, glaciers dropping the ocean, fires, droughts? I already feel that. I just want to do something that doesn’t make me feel like I’m somehow making it worse.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I was hoping that you’d see it differently,” Larry said. “This is going to be a very important year for us, for the world. There’s a new century around the corner, and we’re trying to turn that corner. All of us. And I was hoping that you would be on the team with me, working hard to, as you say, make things better. I just think it’s going to be exciting and challenging and it would be great for us to experience it together.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Honestly, Dad, this has nothing to do with you and me. I’m not doing this to make you feel bad, or look bad. I can’t really explain it. It just feels more comfortable to me,” Mik said, having made up his mind that he was not going to open the curtain on his desire to contribute as little as possible to New Kendall’s drive for world domination."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“So your mind’s made up?” Larry asked."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Mostly,” Mik said, not wanting to say the part about it was that or follow Nila out of town."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Ok,” Larry said. “I just wanted to make sure you’d thought it through. Well, we’re here. Let’s go get you a suit!”<!$Scr_Ps::0><$Scr_Ps::1>"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "* * * * *<!$Scr_Ps::1><$Scr_Ps::0>"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Tomorrow he would submit his choice, AI interfacer, and it would be done. He didn"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’t even really know if it mattered. The ocean didn’t care what your job was when it came roaring up the Charles. The old maple grove near Nila’s theater didn’t suddenly start giving maple syrup again just because you came to your senses and chose Marketing. He’d do his job, go home and do whatever. With whomever. It was all to play, and that was more exciting to him than what team he was on."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“But I couldn’t tell Larry that,” Mik said, trying to explain his awkward shopping trip to Nila."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I never tell Val or Mitch anything,” Nila said. “They’d just use it against me.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“What puzzles me,” Mik said, “is how they act so blind. If I have to hear one more time about ‘the new century,’ I’m going to throw up.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Nila laughed. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“People used to believe that saints and spirits and all sorts of invisible things were going to save them. Now it’s a calendar. Doesn’t that just say it all?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Right, like the world’s big problem is that no one knows what day or date it is.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“You should have heard Kenny Junior’s speech. He actually told them that his father was right, that all the people who tried to stop him were just doomsday naysayers, whatever that means. Like it isn’t doomsday.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Do you think he really believes all of that or does he just pour it on for the troops?” Mik wondered."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I couldn’t hear any notes of doubt, let’s just say that,” Nila said. “And anyway, as long as he’s going to say it and back it up, does it matter?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Huh. Maybe not,” Mik said. “What about your folks? Are they pressuring you to join Security?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“No, because I told them I am joining Sec,” she said."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“No way!”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Oh, I’m not really. But if I told them that, there’d be a drone following me around everywhere. Like instantly.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“So what are you going to do?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I think you know,” she said."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Mik had been dreading this moment. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Yeah, I guess I do. And I’m not surprised. But sad.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“You can do the same,” she said, her voice softer now. “It would be nice.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“It would be,” he said. “But I’m just not ready to do that yet. I’m not as brave as you.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I don’t feel brave. Furious, desperate, yeah, brave, no. Brave would be getting up at school and asking who wants to come with me.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I think it’s brave that you even think these things. I admire what you’re doing. I just can’t bring myself to face so many unknowns, all at once. Especially after watching those fugees trying to cross the river. It wasn’t just that we shot at them. It was how much they had to risk, just to stay alive. That’s one thing we never learn at New K "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " how to stand on your own.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“They’re not on their own. They have each other, and Everywhere. We’re more on our own here in New K.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "He thought about that. Maybe she was right. But he was actually scared of what would happen outside New K. He really had no idea of how he would make a life for himself outside of the corpo world."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“But I know you don’t see it that way,” Nila said. “I’ll miss you.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“And I’ll miss you. I’ve never known anyone like you. Or felt like I do about you. How long do we have?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "She shrugged. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Who knows? But not long. I haven’t figured it all out, but when I do, it’s best you don’t know.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "He leaned over and kissed her. Their kiss trailed off. She kissed him on the forehead and stood up, turned around and walked away. He wanted her to stay, he wanted to talk more about this, but he knew nothing would change. He thought of their first kiss and smiled.<!$Scr_Ps::0>"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        }
