    {
      "id": 18,
      "lineId": 1,
      "beatId": 1,
      "bookId": 1,
      "positionWithinLine": 17,
      "positionInBeat": 0,
      "title": "New mind melds",
      "description": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "<$Scr_Ps::0>Raefe could hear Ines talking with Tosh downstairs. He wanted to learn more about how she had mimicked his signature and fooled the New K attackers and went down to take the opportunity."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Hey, nice to see you,” he said."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“You, too,” she said."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Ines was just telling me that she’s let Mik know that Nila is OK,” Tosh said."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“No need to tangle him to know he’s got a thing for her,” Ines said. “He was hoping she’d settle over this side so he could see her. Now he wants to help somehow. Told him I’d pass that on.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Thanks,” Raefe said. “She, we, are still figuring out what’s safe for her. And us. Her mom’s bad news and it gets worse from there. We’ll have to think on Mik. But, hey, wanted to thank you again for all your help. And to understand what you did. It felt like you can imitate my signature.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Verdad,” Ines said. “Didn’t know that was a new thing. To me, it’s just like hearing someone saying something and then imitating it.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“You can do that with anyone?” he asked."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Not sure. Don’t try it too often. It’s just a little game I played with myself when I had just discovered tangling. Wasn’t too many people I could practice with, but I used to play this game of listening for someone’s mind and then imitating what it felt like.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“But it wasn’t just you,” Tosh said. “I could feel many more.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Yeah, makes sense,” Ines said. “Everywhere, you have your own idea of what tangling is and what it’s for. The rest of us fugees, we do what we do. Like, you don’t put thoughts in people’s heads. For sure, when I sneak into New K and I see a Sec, I put in his head to look away from me.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Raefe felt uneasy. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“You’re right, we do have rules. Well, not rules. We think of it as morals. Just because we can mess with someone’s mind, doesn’t mean we should. Would be like someone really strong thinking it’s alright to threaten people.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Sure, sure,” Ines said. “But you’d send that brother into a fight against the Secs, wouldn’t you?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Fair enough,” Raefe said. “What else do you all do that we don’t?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I don’t know,” she said, slightly annoyed. “We just don’t see it as all or nothing as you. A friend might come into my mind at certain times, you know, that feel good, too. Not just for mayhem!”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Yeah, we do that, too,” Tosh said. “You must think we’re all boring monks or something. But living with each other all the time, we also like to have some boundaries.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“With you there,” she said. “But didn’t you feel it, it wasn’t just that we had Raefe’s signature. We were all clocked, man, we were all like a band playing the same tune. I saw this old vid once when they used to have these giant football matches and 80,000 people were cheering and singing for their team. It was almost like that.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Yeah, I felt that,” Raefe said. “We had those moments in Everywhere "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " once we had 10,000 people singing together. But they were singing "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " not locked together in one mind. We never tried. Fifty years ago, there were still big governments, and some of them wanted everyone to have one mind. Not with empathy "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " just lockstep.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Yeah, my dad told me about that,” Tosh said. “They used to call it brainwashing. Getting everyone not just feeling the same way, but believing some lie, couldn’t talk them out of it.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“And I wonder if the Secs want to try that again,” Raefe said."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“You worry too much,” Ines said. “Secs do what they do. What you do back? That’s what matters now. You know the waters come closer to our feet every day, no? Maybe you find some hill to preach truth from, who’s in the valley listening? Too busy keeping their noses above the water. You have to be alive to do good. First things first.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Raefe sighed. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“And when the Secs find out you can do this, and they figure out how to do it themselves, what then?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I’ll think on that,” she said. “But you think on it, too. You know way more about this than I do. Maybe there’s a way. Because when we were all together, we had something there. We don’t need to agree on everything. You’re the one always telling me we need to work together, fight together. I thought you’d be up on this.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Raefe smiled. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I can see I need to get up on this. And think on it, like you say.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Think on this, too,” Ines said. “Everywhere, you have your way of tangling. Me, someother fugees, who know who else, we have our way. Not just our way, our reasons for doing it. And then you have all the others. Like Mik. He’s easy to tangle with, but he can’t do it. How you put all that together? ‘Cause, you have to admit, if the plan was get everyone to be like Everywhere, you had your chance.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Maybe it just takes a long time,” Tosh said, a little too sharply."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“No, she’s right,” Raefe said. “I’ve been wrestling with that. Everywhere is a beautiful thing, but it’s a big world. Maybe someday we’ll all be tied into the waveform like it was breathing or walking. But, like she says, we have to stay alive first.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "They talked some more, trying to understand where to go. In the end, they realized they needed time. They needed other opinions. For now, they had bought time to figure it out.<!$Scr_Ps::0>"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        }
