    {
      "id": 19,
      "lineId": 1,
      "beatId": 2,
      "bookId": 1,
      "positionWithinLine": 0,
      "positionInBeat": 1,
      "title": "Do North",
      "description": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Do North"
                }
              ],
              "isBold": true
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Radisson, Quebec"
                }
              ],
              "isBold": true
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "April, 2099"
                }
              ],
              "isBold": true
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Mik and Nila had left Val D"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’Or the day before, hitching a ride on a truck bringing food north through ever sparser country to Radisson, on the banks of the La Grande River. Most of the day, they could have been traveling through the same place any time in the last 10,000 years and seen the same view, nearly devoid of human imprint. But as they had come around the last bend into Radisson, suddenly they were in a bustling town, horns honking, traffic lights, streets full of people."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "They hoisted their packs and found their way to the address they had been given back home. It was on a side street off the main drag, a plain little house with nothing more than a house number to identify it. They knocked, half worrying they had the wrong address, or the wrong city even. A small woman with pulled back straight hair, streaked with gray, answered the door."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Hi, we’re Nila and Mik from Boston,” Nila said. “We’re on our way to Thunberg and we were told to come here.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Come on in. I’m Noreen Cheechoo and you’re in the right place,” she said. She showed them to a room in the back where they could bunk overnight. They sat in the front room while she made tea."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“So, you’re the kids from New Kendall, eh?” Noreen said."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“From, as in left it, not of it,” Mik said. “If you get my drift.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Noreen laughed. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Oh yeah, I figured that. New Kendall would be more likely to send armed drones then two kids. Tell me what brings you here.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“How much do you know about New Kendall?” Nila asked. “I mean, everyone knows about the company, but we live in the town.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Well, you’re right, I know about the company "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " they really make sure everyone knows them, don’t they? What’s the town like?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Where to start?” Nila said. “Let’s just say it’s a weird place. It’s a gated community, basically, where all the corpos and the few thousand  people who run the company live. The best thing about it is it’s high and dry, which is not so easy on the East Coast of North America these days.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“And the worst thing about it,” Mik jumped in, “is that they’ll do anything to keep everyone else out, even if they have to shoot them. And I don’t mean people from the other side of the world, not that that’s right either, but they’ll shoot people on the other side of the river who try to come over to high ground during storms when the river floods.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“So we just finished high school,” Nila said, “and in New Kendall that means they assign you to a job, whether you want that job or not. And we just don’t want to be part of their whole messed up corpo thing. We read up on a lot of different stuff and we really like the whole idea of Thunberg. We want to be part of that.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“It’s not a vacation, you know,” Noreen said. “It might be more than you’re ready for as far as hard work goes. Ever dug a ditch, or worked a farm?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“No,” Mik said. “But we’re not afraid of that. We’re young, healthy, we figure it’ll take a bit, but we should be just as able to do that as anyone else. Right?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Yeah, just that,” Nila said. “We know we’re soft and we have a lot to learn. That’s why we want to be part of it.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Well, you’ve got the right attitude,” Noreen said. “I’m gonna tell you straight up, with people from these corpo fortresses, we’ve learned we have to be real careful. Not everyone is who they say they are. So in a little while, a nurse is going to come and she’s going to verify some stuff about you. She’ll take DNA, she’ll scan you for implants, stuff like that. Are you good with that?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "They looked at each other. Heaven had bouncers, it seemed. Nila felt Mik"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’s agreement. She nodded for the both of them."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Ok, I’ll let her know,” Noreen said. “While we’re waiting, would you like some tea?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "She brought them some kind of herbal tea."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“This is good,” Mik said. “What kind is it?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Local stuff, some herbs and some moss,” Noreen said. “People have been drinking that here for thousands of years.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Are you First Nations?” Nila asked."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Yes, Wakaganish Cree,” Noreen said. “Born and raised not far from here. Back when no one wanted the land. Better to give us this then Montreal, I guess was how they looked at it a century ago. Now some of them want it back, or they want to shit all over it just like they did in the south.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Yeah, it looks like a mall parking lot before Christmas out there on Main Street,” Mik said. “We thought it was going to be more different.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Oh, don’t worry, Thunberg is not like anywhere you’ve been. And most of these jokers here couldn’t even find it with a map. I’ll take you there in the morning, though.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“That’s a relief,” Nila said. “Still, it’s sad that people are wrecking this place. If they want to live unsustainably, why don’t they just stay where they were?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Well, that’s a good question,” Noreen said. “I don’t want to be too harsh. Some of them, there’s no there anymore where they were "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " it’s underwater, it’s desert, there’s no more drinking water, well, you know all of that. Most of them, really, that’s their story. But then there’s also the ones that want to be the next Ken Robertson, if you know what I mean.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Oh, yeah, we know exactly what you mean,” Nila said. “But about the others, the fugees, it’s a bit surprising that they’re crapping up the place. Back home, the fugees and the corpos hate each other. Some of the fugees are amazing. You know about REM?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Sure, who doesn’t?” Noreen said. “We’re in touch with Everywhere. But like everything else, some people learn, some people don’t. And it seems like the fugees who don’t learn come to places like Hudson Bay because they think it’s their time to get their piece of the almighty pie. So just be careful here "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " not everyone is a saint, or even just a nice person.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "There was a knock on the door and a young woman with a medical bag came in. Noreen introduced her as Kaitlyn. Also short, compact, she worked quickly taking blood and saliva that went into a small machine for analysis. She slowly passed a short wand from head to toe over each of them."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Ok, no implants, so we know you’re not wired for sound,” Kaitlyn said. “Now I’m going to take the data from your samples and check them against your New Kendall health records.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“You can do that?” Mik said."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Don’t worry,” Kaitlyn said, cracking a smile for the first time. “They’ll never know about it, so they can’t backtrack you to here. Let’s just say we have modernized our hunting and fishing skills to include data. Here we go "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " Mik Albertson, son of Tyfnie and Ray-Juan and Nila Edwards, daughter of…hey, what the fuck? Did you think you’d get away with this?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“What?” Nila said. “What’s the problem?” She was too startled to try and read Kaitlyn’s emotions."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Tell me who your parents are,” Kaitlyn said."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“My mom is Lillith Edwards. I don’t know who my dad is. I never met him and she never told me.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Listen, we have a problem,” Noreen said, looking at the puter over Kaitlyn’s shoulder. “Your mother is secret police for New Kendall and your dad is, well let’s just say he’s a problem.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I know my mom’s a Sec, but that’s partly why I’m here, to get away from her and her awful corpo boyfriend "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " not my father "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " who does even worse stuff. You’re going to bounce me for that?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“No, we’re not going to turn you away, not just yet,” Noreen said. “But we need to be sure. There’s an easy way for us to solve this.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Nila felt Noreen"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’s mind brush up against her. “You want to tangle with me?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Well, it would be Kaitlyn, and it would be both of you. Are you OK with that?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Mik, are you OK with that?” Nila asked. “Do you want to talk about it?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Just like when you tried it with me, right?” Mik asked."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“How deep did you go?” Kaitlyn asked Nila."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I don’t know, he’s like the only person I ever did it with, except, actually, REM himself. Long story "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " you can have the memory if you don’t believe me. But I’m not like some big expert tangler.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Show me how you did it with him,” Kaitlyn said, point at Mik. “ But use that to show me the memory of Raefe.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Nila took a deep breath and tried to calm the rising panic. They had come more than a thousand miles to the edge of the world to start anew, and yet they couldn"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’t escape the very thing they had fled. She felt Kaitlyn’s mind, open but not all the way, like a road with fences on either side. She found an opening in the fence and let her mind walk through it. She had entered a room with calming, dull red walls. It felt warm and welcoming. She relaxed and recalled sitting outside the office in New Kendall, connecting with Raefe on the other side of the wall, listening to the meeting through him."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Thanks,” Kaitlyn said. “You are stronger than you think. I won’t  need to go deeper than that with you, Mik.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Mik nodded. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Go ahead.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Nila was already tangled with Mik. She could feel Kaitlyn enter his mind. It was weird to witness someone else this. She couldn"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’t tell what Kaitlyn found, but she withdrew. Nila felt Kaitlyn connect with Noreen. She was telling her what she had learned, that Mik was clean, that Nila was complicated but not here under false pretenses. Her mother was a Sec and her father was not in their picture anymore."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "And then Nila knew who her father was. And why her mother had never told her. And she wanted to vomit and scream and punch a hole in the wall all at the same time."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Are you, OK?” Mik asked. “You look pale.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Kaitlyn"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’s face softened. “I’m so sorry. I should have realized you would sense what I shared with Noreen. You shouldn’t have had to learn about it that way.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Learn what?” Mik asked."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Nothing!” Nila said, struggling to keep it together. “I’ll tell you later. Are we done now? Are you going to let us stay or did we come all this way for nothing?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“We’re good,” Noreen said. “But we had to know that you weren’t here to fuck things up. You wouldn’t have been the first. I’m sorry it went down this way, but we really had no choice.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "*****"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Later, Noreen made them a dinner of salmon from the Bay, with some local turnipy kind of root and some big fat tomatoes from her garden. Even without tangling, Nila could tell Noreen was trying to be kind, feeling bad about the afternoon"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’s shocking revelation. That was still banging around in Nila’s head and she couldn’t make it settle down. She had left home, but home hadn’t left her, not just yet. She permitted herself to think about it more while they helped Noreen clean up, but it was still too big and raw to get a bead on it. She had no idea of what to do with this new information. Was there really anything to do?"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Mik was geared up to go out on the town. She thought he was looking to get silly after being cooped up in New Kendall, with its strict limits on drugs and alcohol. She agreed to go with him to investigate the local brews in the town"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’s many bars. Once they were out of Noreen’s earshot, he couldn’t contain himself."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“So who’s your old man?” he said, as if maybe her dad were some famous vid star or footy player."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“No one you’d want to know,” she said."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Oh, sorry,” he said. “Did you know him?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Not personally,” she said, “but yea, I know who he is. It’s not just who he is, though…”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“What?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“It’s also the circumstances…”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“The circumstances?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Listen, I’m not ready for this, OK,” she said. “It’s put my mom, my whole life, in a different light. I have to think about this.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Ok, I’ll let it go. But you’re not having second thoughts about this, are you?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“No, no, if anything, I’m even more convinced this was the right thing to do. The farther away as I can get from her, from them, the better off I’ll be.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Good. If you want to talk about it, let me know.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Yeah, thanks. Now, let’s get fucked up.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Mik and Nila arrive in Hudson's Bay. Nila finds out that Ken Robertson Jr. is her dad"
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        }
      ],
