    {
      "id": 20,
      "lineId": 1,
      "beatId": 2,
      "bookId": 1,
      "positionWithinLine": 1,
      "positionInBeat": 1,
      "title": "Out for a walk",
      "description": [
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "children": [
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Out for a walk"
                }
              ],
              "isBold": true
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "April, 2020"
                }
              ],
              "isBold": true
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Hey, old man, want to go for a walk?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Raefe laughed. Tosh always liked to tease him. Sometimes people looked sideways at him for it, but Raefe appreciated it, actually. Took the Saint Raefe pressure off him."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Sure. Where did you have in mind?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I heard New Kendall made their first delivery to the bus yard. I was thinking of walking up there, no bikes.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "So they went up Mass Ave. Spring had arrived full on, the leaves now hiding some of the crumbling buildings. In the winter, it could look mighty grim "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " acres of decay. Now at least there was the perennial carnival of green to interrupt that."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Do you think the trees are laughing at us?” Tosh asked. “Being a tree here is a pretty good deal, eh? No more cruel winters.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Yeah, but they hate the storms,” Raefe countered."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“You can tangle with them?” Tosh kidded him."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“You can’t?” Raefe replied, giving it right back."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“The son of Alton Winchester, master of sustainable agriculture? Are you kidding? When I was small, sometimes I had to ask the plants to let my dad know I was around.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Raefe smiled. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“He’d be proud of you, that I know. He was a good man. If anyone had been able to tangle with plants, it would have been him. I don’t know if Everywhere would have happened without him.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Raefe could feel Tosh"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’s unspoken thought: it was a lot to live up to. And he had, when Raefe thought about it."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“And I don’t know where Cambridge would be without you, Tosh. You’ve become such a force for good in the community.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Tosh said nothing, but he smiled, and Raefe could feel that he took the compliment. They had arrived at the bus yard. Raefe saw Pedro and waved. He was standing next to a large collection of pallets, loaded down with all sorts of stuff. From a distance it looked like a junkyard on skids."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Well, I got to hand it to you,” Pedro said. “The New Kendall crowd did actually deliver.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Anything useful?” Tosh asked."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Oh, yeah,” Pedro said. “Might not look it, but we made sure. Right here is a lot of building materials "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " brick, some wood, some metal roofing. On the other side, there’s actually some furniture. Chairs, tables, stuff like that.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“What can you do with it?” Raefe asked Pedro."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“We can build some shelters, repair some houses. Maybe enough for 200 people.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“That’s great,” Raefe said. “Could you use more?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Absolutely,” Pedro said. “Hit me with another load like this, I’d say.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“It’s in their interest, too,” Tosh said. “Keeps us on this side of the river longer. I’ll put the word out. They’re still tearing down in Boston, so they’ll have more. Three months good?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Yeah, take us that long to deal with this load.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Raefe could feel Pedro was feeling good about it, no longer consumed by thoughts of hitting back. Not that far from the surface, though, so he and Tosh would have to try hard to keep things going."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Hey,” Pedro said. “Ines wanted me to give you this. Somebody found it down near the Mass Ave bridge a couple of weeks ago. Seems like a kid over in New Kendall threw it over the river.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Raefe took a bottle from him. Inside was a letter. He unfolded it and read it, Tosh looking over his shoulder."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "To the people south of the river:"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "I want to tell you how sorry some of us up here are about the people that got killed in the flood. I was there and I saw it go down. They made us kids in high school be lookouts at the checkpoints. We saw the Secs shooting. It was horrible and wrong! You should just know that we don"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’t all hate you. The people who run this town are sick and I’m sick of them. I’m leaving and other young people are too. I wish I could help more, but I don’t know how. I’ve decided to go to one of the model farms in Canada. Maybe they have the right idea "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " make a world everyone can live in. Maybe that can make up for what happened here. We have to make a better future!"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Yours,"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Sad, frustrated, angry but hopeful"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Thanks,” Raefe said. “I want to smile and cry at the same time.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Yeah, lot of that going around,” Pedro said. “But Ines wanted you to see it. And she won’t say it, but I will: you were right about not killing them. And she knows that now. She probably knew it then but didn’t want to admit it.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "And Pedro turned and went back to unloading the pallets. Raefe knew that had cost Pedro something and just said "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Good luck with this. See you around.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "He and Tosh walked back down to Porter Square, enjoying the trees, the walk, and their small victory. It occurred to Raefe that Tosh probably had already known about the bottle and that Pedro was placated by the deliveries but had let Raefe find it out first hand to cheer him up. Who"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’s leading who now, he smiled to himself. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "As they walked he thought of the young woman who had reached out to him that day in New Kendall. Was she who had written the letter? Offhand, he couldn"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’t sense her. Had she already gone to Canada? And where? There were so many places where people were settling the newly warm tundra up there. Would it live up to her hopes?"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“So many young people are drawn to these experiments,” Tosh said, reading him. “It’s their generation’s chance, I think. To get out of this mess, to have a fresh start, with a clean slate.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“How much do you know about these farms?” Raefe asked."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Not too much,” Tosh said. “They keep a low profile. They’re not even all farms, really. Some do aquaculture. Some do radical chemical engineering, even. Instead of mining or drilling for oil, like in the old days, they turn carbon dioxide or methane into building materials, or fuel cells. Drawing down greenhouse gases, locking them into useful stuff using solar energy. Nothing new there, but they specialize in doing it on a small scale, with cheap and dirty materials.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Like your dad,” Raefe said. “He was the one who got everyone started on that.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“For sure,” Tosh said. “But he didn’t know you could do it without plants, just engineering bacteria. Even with all the chaos, little groups of scientists kept at it and then they went off the grid with it after 2082. They didn’t trust their corporate sponsors anymore "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " after all, another Billy Warren was sure to come along. And Robertson survived the whole thing, obviously. They went rogue and now there’s this whole subculture of sustainable biohackers.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Which a lot of people are still suspicious of,” Raefe said."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“For good reason,” Tosh said. “Don’t mess with Mother Nature and all of that. But this crowd is different. They look deeply into how the natural world works. They go slow and they don’t care about profit. And when they screw up, they change course.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "I bet Des knows all about this, Raefe thought to himself. My engineering genius son "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " how did that happen? He realized he didn"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’t even know what it was that Des was up to at the moment. He’d have to investigate."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "When they got back to Porter Square, he begged off the rest of the day and went home. The walk had left him tired and that was a good excuse to leave. He had other things on his mind and he wanted to find Lina before she went to sleep. He climbed the stairs of his apartment building to the roof. He liked to come up here at nights to watch the stars some nights. Since city had shrunk, it had also gotten darker and when the moon was absent, you could almost see the Milky Way. Sometimes he liked to imagine that he could see Traveller"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’s Perch. But today it was a nice spring afternoon, already warming into the 70s with a gentle breeze. It seemed he couldn’t get enough of the trees today. From six stories up, much of surrounding land was hidden by the blooming canopy. It wasn’t the forest, but at least he couldn’t see all the daily reminders of how far the city had fallen."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "He calmed himself and let Lina find him."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Hello, my love. Have I caught you at a good time?” he asked."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Of course,” she said. “The night is just coming on. And how are you, my love?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Good, I think. New Kendall made good on their promises, some of their youth are rebelling and leaving, and the Norcambs have decided maybe it was right to turn away from revenge.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“That is good to hear. You really sounded up against it a couple of weeks ago. Are you feeling more settled now?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Well, I think I’m feeling clearer. Maybe not more settled. Maybe that was my problem, Lina.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“How so?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“How can we be ‘settled’ in this world? It is constantly changing "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " the weather, the sea, the rivers, the plants "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " and it will keep changing for many generations. I wanted to be settled, I wanted to rest. But I don’t think it is to be.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Oh, Raefe, you are 71. It is OK to rest. You are not the last person alive.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“No, you are right. And I was realizing that today. I was realizing that Tosh has grown into a middle-aged man of great insight and skill. He has become a leader, at least here. People see me as the leader and him as the helper, but I think the truth is the other way around. I bless his ideas and people listen. But I see that he also can persuade, that his empathic skills have blossomed, and that he is ready to take over my role, at least here.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Yes, it’s a comfort to see the next generation bloom. But I sense there is more on your mind.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Indeed. A kid from New Kendall left a note for the Norcambs. They wanted to apologize for the shootings. They were there, apparently, and were horrified. And then they said something that really made an impression on me. It was "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "I"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’ve decided to go to one of the model farms in Canada. Maybe they have the right idea "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " make a world everyone can live in. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "And then "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "We have to make a better future."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Well, that is hopeful. Too bad they left."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Yes, I thought that, too. But then it struck me, no, good that they left. Because they left to do something, to be somewhere where they could change things. Like we had to go to Dadaab, they had to go north.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Do you know them?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Maybe,” he said and told her about the girl, Nila, he had tangled with in New Kendall. “I will try to find her in the waveform and encourage her. And thank her "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " the note changed minds in Norcamb.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“That’s great.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“But that’s not enough. You know why I’m stuck?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I think you are going to tell me.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Because I’ve stuck myself on this patch of land because it once was my home and I’ve been staring it down now for years, daring it to live up to my hopes. And that was unreasonable. The people here have their own struggles and they will find their way in time, but in their time. You know, I heard from our friend from far away.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“No! The birds or the fish?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "He smiled. She always thought of them that way. "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“The bird from Mars. And she said something truly wise, as is their way. That our lives are so short. Do you know her partner is 1,200 years old? She says that she didn’t understand how much that shapes us, that we can never expect to see the fruits of our efforts fully realized. I don’t mean you and me, I mean all people. It’s just who we are.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“How strange after all these years! But I could have told you that we are only mortal.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“No, no, I know that. But it made me realize that my dream of a wave of empaths changing the world is a long-term dream. Not even Mari or Des will see it or even the generation after them. And I stuck myself here as if I couldn’t leave for a minute or I might miss the wave. And now rebel kids from all over are building new lives in new places and tangling is just a small part of it. What we set in motion will live long after us.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“And that is great, is it not?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Yes, it’s fantastic. It’s the answer, or the beginnings of one. Or many answers. I don’t know. But I want to find out.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Ah, that’s what I was sensing. You are going to go walkabout, aren’t you?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Well, now that you say it, yes. I’m going to see for myself some of these experiments, these fresh ideas. And just so you don’t think I’ve completely lost it, I think you’ll agree that we always find that when people pull together and can realize these sorts of projects, their empathy also blooms. So I can look and learn, but I can also teach them about tangling, if they don’t already know.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I agree. I’m so happy that you’ve decided this. You know we’ll all support you however you need it. If you want, I’ll come join you. I’ve my own Toshes over here who are also ready if the old lady would just get out of the way.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“That would be wonderful. But let me spend a few months exploring. When I find a place that makes sense, you can sail over and we can be together again. Or if not, we’ll wander together. But I need to walk on my own for just a bit.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Well, take good shoes,” she said, and he could feel her laughter. It had been awhile."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Are the stars out yet?” he asked."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“No, not just yet,” she said. “Later, I will blow a kiss to your far off friend when I see her home.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“And now I do that for you, my love. I will find you soon. Be well until then.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "He was excited, he realized. For the first time in a long time, he would be doing something new, something promising. He started making a mental list of all the things he needed to do, the people that he needed to talk to, before setting off. And then he had a thought. He reached out into the waveform and found her."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I just wanted you to know,” he said, “that I’m going to be gone for awhile. Maybe it was our little talk, maybe it was some of the things going on here. But I’m going to try something new.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“That sounds like good news,” Diver said. “What will you do?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I want to find young people who may not be walking my path, but are already building a new kind of world. I’m sure you know that here on Earth, the northern latitudes have been cold and barely settled for thousands of years. And now in some places the climate is quite moderate, the permanent snow and ice gone, and huge tracts of fertile land are exposed. Young people who have flocked to these areas, building new kinds of farms, factories, houses and so on. I want to meet them and learn from them.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“What do you hope will happen?”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I don’t know, but I think I’ve just been stuck here, banging my head against a wall. I’ve alway known that empathy alone would not change the world. But in the beginning, I was so worried that the climate crisis would  lead us to tear ourselves apart and that empathy would at least stop that. And I think it did, to a degree. But now we must also think about what’s next. Maybe things don’t move in simple straight lines. I feel deep down that these kids are doing something important. And that maybe it’s people like that who will be the carriers of empathy now.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“You’ve had so many attempts like that "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " Everywhere, of course, but also all those groups that came to Dadaab.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“Yes, and the ones that actually built communities "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " Dadaab, the Rising Tide, there were others "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "—"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": " they’re still here and they’ve had an impact. So I think that maybe empathy can’t just rest at understanding. It has to be transformative, not just of our hearts and souls, but of the physical world, too. Otherwise, it all just gets worn down by the usual frictions.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I admit, I am surprised. You seemed exhausted. And now you want to make this journey.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "“I surprise myself, to be honest. Maybe I’m just a foolish old man. But I’m not going to sit around here for the next 10 or 20 years until I die, whining about how little effect I’m having or pining for the old days with the Urban Gypsies. It’s time to admit that the torch has been passed, and to see what light it brings.”"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "They talked for awhile longer, Diver remembering that she still knew very little about humans, Raefe wanting her to feel that she was not wrong to help them. The years had put distance between them, but now he was remembering her strength and wisdom and how good it felt to have her on his side. On humanity"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "’s side, really."
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Discovery, Information Analytics, Ambassadors, Administration and Timelines"
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "type": "paragraph",
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Green from Timelines, Hankori from Administration, Putnomo from Discovery, Tanoch from Ambasssadors and Manulo from Analysis "
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "children": [
                {
                  "text": "Raefe and Lina have a long talk. She wants him to come to Africa. He's not so sure. He's restless. He decides to go walkabout, trying to buy time to figure things out."
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        }
